Appendix 3            11          
OUTLINE TERMS OF REFERENCE FOR CONSULTANTS 

1.  The  consultants  will  have  demonstrated  project-related  experience  and  extensive 
experience in Central Asia or countries with similar conditions to the proposed Project. Each 
specialist will review background studies associated with their assignments and familiarize 
themselves with recent and ongoing initiatives relevant to their activities and outputs. Given the 
uncertainties associated with climate change and the lack of up-to-date hydrometeorological 
data, combined with the Pyanj River’s function as the international border between Afghanistan 
and Tajikistan, an innovative and flexible approach will be required by the regional technical 
assistance  (RETA)  team.  Where  international  and  national  specialists  are  required,  the 
international specialist will take responsibility for managing the national consultants’ output 
schedule and providing quality control. 

2.  Flood  Management  Engineers  and  Specialists  and  Team  Leader and  Deputies 
(international, 18 person months; Afghan, 22 person-months; Tajik, 22 person-months). The 
team leader (and deputy team leaders) will have the same technical responsibilities as the flood 
management  engineers,  but  will  also  be  responsible  for  flood  preparedness  activities  and 
overall RETA management. The water resources and flood management specialist will  
(i)  establish the administrative and logistical arrangements for effective functioning of 
the RETA team;  
(ii)  interact  with  governments  at  national,  provincial,  and  district  levels;  and  with 
nongovernment organizations and other stakeholders working in the sector;  
(iii)  compile  and  evaluate  sector  assessments  related  to  flood  management  in 
Afghanistan  and  Tajikistan,  background  reports,  surveys,  and  data,  including 
compiling a listing of agencies and nongovernment organizations working in the 
project area (identification of relevant materials should be led by the Afghan and 
Tajik deputy team leaders and their counterparts);  
(iv)  coordinate the inputs of the other specialists, delivery of outputs, and quality control; 
coordinate work with other relevant projects and project outputs; and report to the 
Asian Development Bank (ADB);  
(v)  support the assessment of the overall performance of existing flood defenses and 
river training works in Afghanistan and Tajikistan, and identify and assess the state 
of unprotected river banks;  
(vi)  assess factors leading to erosion and failure of existing flood defenses and river 
banks;  
(vii)  carry out specify studies with regard to additional work on hydrology and morphology;  
(viii)  coordinate a review of flood experiences as they relate to formulation of the flood 
management programs and implementation of local flood management strategies;  
(ix)  recommend appropriate levels of flood protection based on the degree of risk and 
vulnerability of local communities, key infrastructure, and agricultural land;  
(x)  prioritize  feasibility  studies  for  structural  and  nonstructural  flood  management 
measures;  
(xi)  in support to the river morphologists and hydrologists, consider alternative layouts 
and types of flood defenses;  
(xii)  recommend  modern  design  procedures,  construction  materials,  and  construction 
methods appropriate to the local context and topographic survey standards;  
(xiii)  prepare a paper on options for sustainable operations and maintenance (O&M) of 
flood protection and irrigation infrastructure, focusing on institutions and financing, 
including affordability, and capacity building needs;  
(xiv)  review existing and planned flood forecasting and warning systems for the Pyanj 
River Basin in Afghanistan and Tajikistan;
